<TEXT>
hurricane dean drifted northward friday in the open 
atlantic ocean after veering away from northern caribbean islands 
and the southeastern bahamas forecasters said 
it may strengthen a little bit there are changes that are 
taking place around it said bob sheets director of the national 
hurricane center in suburban coral gables 
at 1030 pm edt deans winds of 85 mph were centered near 
230 north latitude and 6491 west longitude about 600 miles 
southeast of bermuda the hurricane was moving north at about 12 
mph forecasters said 
our latest reconnaissance positions indicate that indeed it 
may start a little bit more fast speed toward the north and you 
can see that on the satellite sheets said 
a weakening of upper atmosphere currents that steer the storm 
kept dean away from the islands thursday after it initially headed 
toward the virgin islands and puerto rico 
the hurricane was moving very slowly 
were still expecting it to turn to the north and then 
eventually go to the northeast said forecaster jim gross asked 
about the storms potential for hitting bermuda in about three 
days he said theyre very easy to miss 
the second hurricane of the atlantic season became a tropical 
storm monday night and was reclassified a hurricane tuesday when 
its maximum sustained wind speed passed 74 mph 
