more than 50 people were injured when a 
crowd trying to get into a standingroomonly area for a friday 
evening grandstand concert at the ohio state fair pressed into the 
area before it was opened 
state highway patrol troopers at the scene said most of the 
injuries were minor shane jenkins director of public relations 
said 58 people were treated at the fair about a dozen later were 
taken to hospitals 
doctors hospital north nursing supervisor melanie crader said 
eight teenagers were treated for minor injuries i think there 
was one broken foot but it was pretty minor stuff there were 
varying complaints she said 
after the disturbance gov richard f celeste met with fair 
officials and managers of the acts scheduled to appear friday night 
following the meeting the manager for one of the acts new kids 
on the block announced that the entertainment would be presented 
one act at a time and if authorities felt the crowd was getting 
unruly the rest of the show would be canceled 
after the announcement celeste walked along the perimeter of 
the grandstand telling concertgoers to be cool and pass it 
back 
trooper gary esslinger said he could not estimate the size of 
the crowd for the 8 pm concert the crowd had been building all 
day and the grandstand was largely filled by late afternoon 
witnesses said 
the standingroomonly area had not been opened when the crowd 
broke for the seats witnesses said a thunderstorm broke shortly 
after the crowd rushed into the area adding to the confusion 
