<TEXT>
congress passed and sent to president bush 
early saturday a landmark savings and loan bailout providing tens 
of billions of dollars to cover the losses of savers whose deposits 
disappeared in a wave of fraudulent lending 
by 201175 the house passed the 159 billion financial rescue 
the biggest in the nations history following a frantic 48 hours 
of negotiations between congress and the bush administration 
the senate approved the measure only two hours earlier giving 
president bush a victory on his first and biggest legislative 
initiative since taking office last january as congress recesses 
for a month bush had agreed in advance to the compromise the 
second in as many days 
the bill provides 50 billion over the next three years to close 
and merge 500 insolvent sampls and pay off savers whose billions of 
dollars in government insured deposits were lost to failed and 
often fraudulent loans most of them in texas 
it also totally overhauls the regulation of the industry to try 
to fulfill bushs promise that never again will taxpayers be 
asked to pay for losses sampl owners will be required to put 
billions of dollars more of their own money at risk as a buffer 
between risky loans and the federal deposit insurance funds 
the administration lobbied house republicans throughout the day 
to provide the winning margin as democrats defected from the bill 
in large numbers in response to a compromise hiding most of the 
cleanup costs off the budget and out of the official federal 
deficit 
republicans in the house supported the bill 11940 while 
democrats opposed it 13582 fiftyone members did not vote and 
five voted present 
rep sam gibbons dfla accused house members of losing their 
conscience and their backbone in bowing to a veto threat from bush 
and agreeing to financing the bulk of the bailouts costs through 
30year bonds 
it should have been paid for by taxes but the president could 
not bring himself to say the word said gibbons so we have 
fostered this unconscionable debt on our children and 
grandchildren 
but with the losses of federally insured deposits mounting at a 
rate of 20 million to 30 million a day supporters said it would 
be equally unconscionable for congress to go on vacation without 
fixing the problem 
i for one dont want to take the chance of another 
bankholiday crisis said rep chalmers wylie rohio referring 
to the wave of bank closings at the end of the hoover 
administration in early 1933 that deepened the great depression 
the alternative are unthinkable added rep steve bartlett 
rtexas 
the savings of million of americans are at stake unless we do 
something sen christopher bond dmo said just before the 
unusual divison vote in which supporters and opponents indicate 
their position by standing 
the procedure leaves no record of who votes yes or no but four 
senators stood in opposition and three others asked to be recorded 
as opponents they were sens bob graham dfla kent conrad 
dnd charles grassley riowa james exon dneb wendell ford 
dky john warner rva and jay rockefeller rwva 
i think it is the best bill possible to craft under the 
circumstances said sen donald riegle jr chairman of the 
senate banking committee it will make major reforms in every 
area 
president bush was on the phone with house members from both 
parties throughout the day according to sources pleading for 
support and treasury secretary nicholas f brady was dispatched to 
the capitol hill to negotiate a resolve to the impasse 
brady a former appointed republican senator from new jersey 
spent nearly an hour on the senate floor lobbying former colleagues 
senate majority leader george mitchell took the bill the senate 
floor only after brady and rep john dingell dmich chairman of 
the house energy and commerce committee reached an accord on 
offbudget bonds 
dingell had demanded that the offbudget bonds to be used for 
much of the financing be registered with the securities and 
exchange commission as carrying a risk higher than normal 
government securities he and brady agreed that the sec may demand 
full disclosure to investors of risks but the bill does not require 
registration 
dingell earlier friday joined with three other committee 
chairmen to oppose the thursday accord reps dan rostenkowski 
dill leon panetta dcalif and john conyers dmich dingell 
leads the energy and commerce committee rostenskowski chairs ways 
and means panetta is in charge of budget and conyers heads 
government operations 
</TEXT>
