<DOCNO> AP890805-0012 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
abbott laboratories is marketing a new test that 
detects the aids virus rather than the bodys response to the virus 
and can reveal infection weeks earlier than currently used tests 
the company said friday 
aidsvirus tests now in use detect the presence of antibodies 
proteins manufactured by white blood cells to fight invading 
organisms antibodies usually appear in a persons system six to 10 
weeks after infection 
the new test detects aids antigens proteins on the surface of 
the invading virus the new test can signal the presence of the 
antigens about two weeks after infection a spokesman for the north 
chicagobased company said 
this test complements the antibody test it does not replace 
the antibody test said dr harold kessler associate professor 
of medicine and director of the hiv treatment program at 
rushpresbyterianst lukes medical center 
test was approved thursday for commercial sale by the us food 
and drug administration making it the only approved test for the 
aids virus in the country 
though antigens are the first detectable sign of infection they 
effectively disappear with the appearance of antibodies which 
remain in the body the antigen test is thus not always able to 
reveal the presence of infection 
antigens only reappear when the virus becomes more active a 
possible signal that the infected person will get sick either with 
immune problems with a mild form of aids known as aidsrelated 
complex or with fullblown aids said kessler 
to identify which infected people are likely to develop symptoms 
some may be infected for years without any symptoms doctors can 
check patients with the new test every three or four months said 
abbott spokesman charles weber 
if you come up where the antigen test is positive that might 
be the opportune moment to intervene with azt or some form of 
antiviral therapy weber said azt or zidovudine is the only 
drug approved by the fda for fighting aids 
kessler said antigenpositive patients have a 75 percent chance 
of developing symptoms compared with 29 percent for 
antigennegative patients 
the new test available under the trade name hiv ag1 is 
already under manufacture because is has previously been used to 
monitor the effectiveness of azt it will continue to be valuable 
for that purpose kessler said 
kessler said the test will probably cost 100 to 120 at the 
lab which is not out of line with other laboratory tests for 
viruses 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

