<TEXT>
a psychologist intends to appeal a federal 
court ruling that allows a journalist quoting a public figure to 
make up a quote if the quote does not alter the substantive 
content of what was said 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals ruled on friday that 
jeffrey masson a former director of the freud archives could not 
sue writer janet malcolm for 102 million over a new yorker 
magazine article and book that allegedly quoted him as saying many 
things he never said 
the purported quotes included massons selfdescription as an 
intellectual gigolo his comment that after sigmund freud he 
would be regarded as the greatest analyst who ever lived and a 
statement that he would have turned the freud house into a place 
of sex women fun 
in a libel suit by a public figure who must prove that harmful 
statements were deliberately or recklessly false quotations can be 
fabricated if they are rational interpretations of ambiguous 
remarks or do not alter the substantive content of unambiguous 
remarks said the opinion by judge arthur alarcon he was joined 
in his opinion by judge cynthia holcomb hall 
but the dissenter in the 21 decision judge alex kozinski said 
fabricated quotes were the equivalent of lies 
if authors are given license to invent quotations on the basis 
of what they perceive to be a speakers character there are no 
words whatsoever that they cannot put into a subjects mouth 
kozinski said 
karl olson lawyer for malcolm and her publishers said the 
ruling vindicates his clients he said they never conceded that any 
quotes had been made up or changed other than a word here and a 
word there 
paul kleven a lawyer for masson said the ruling would be 
appealed 
we dont think theres any need to allow that sort of 
alteration to protect the values that the first amendment is 
designed to protect he said 
masson a berkeley resident was fired in 1981 as director of 
the new yorkbased freud archives 
he said he was fired and fell out of favor among psychoanalysts 
because he had written that freud the father of modern 
pscyhoanalysis knew the evidence was to the contrary when he 
declared that women usually fantasized claims of childhood sexual 
abuse 
his suit attacked malcolms 1983 new yorker article trouble 
in the archives and her 1984 book in the freud archives on 
the struggle between masson and directors of the archives over his 
views on freud 
masson said malcolm had maliciously painted a false picture of 
him by fabricating quotes citing numerous statements that were not 
in her taperecorded interviews he also said he notified the new 
yorker and the book publisher of the fabrications before 
publication 
us district judge eugene lynch dismissed the suit in 1987 an 
appeals court upheld his ruling 
kozinski in his dissent said the quotes distorted massons 
taped statements for example he never called himself the greatest 
analyst just the only one who held his views in addition 
kozinski said journalists are supposed to vouch for the accuracy 
of the quotes they use 
he also quoted william shawn editor of the new yorker at the 
time of malcolms articles as calling the magazine the most 
accurate publication not only in this country but in the entire 
world 
</TEXT>
