<TEXT>
responding to the exxon valdez oil spill the 
senate has passed environmentalprotection legislation hailed by 
majority leader george mitchell as reducing the potential for 
damage to our nation 
the measure boosts companies liability for oil spills creates 
a nationwide system to clean them up and establishes a 1 billion 
trust fund to help compensate for damages similar legislation is 
pending in the house 
such legislation had been under consideration for years but the 
issue took on a new sense of urgency after the tanker struck bligh 
reef in alaskas prince william sound rupturing the ships hull 
and spilling 11 million gallons of oil that stained the coastline 
added impetus came from two smallerscale spills over a 24hour 
period off rhode island in the delaware river and in the houston 
ship channel 
the purpose of this bill is to make sure that we never again 
allow an oil spill to become an ecological disaster said sen 
max baucus dmont the bills floor manager 
this legislation when enacted into law will discourage such 
oil spills in the future and reduce the potential for damage to our 
nation said mitchell dmaine who worked for passage of 
oilspill legislation for eight years 
and if they do occur they will be cleaned up and compensated 
much more readily than has been the case he said 
the bill was approved 990 with sen david durenberger 
rminn not voting 
the legislation directs that contingency plans be drawn for 
dealing with oil spills on land and water and requires the 
establishment of cleanup teams with preplaced equipment 
the 1 billion trust fund will be financed by a 3centabarrel 
fee or tax on all domestic and imported petroleum 
the bill provides for increasing the limit of compensation for 
each oil spill from 500 million to 1 billion 
in alaska gov steve cowper praised the action 
this bill is a major step forward for alaska and all other 
coastal states whose residents face enormous economic 
environmental and human damage from oil spills cowper said in 
fairbanks this bill wont end the suffering but it will make 
major spills less likely and the response to them quicker and 
better 
in acting on a series of amendments the senate sharply raised 
an owners liability for compensating for oil spills and their 
destruction of property and the environment 
the legislation preserves the authority of the states to impose 
unlimited liability if they wish and to impose their own oil spill 
standards and requirements set up cleanup or compensation funds 
and levy fees and penalties 
it also gives the president extensive authority to take overall 
charge of cleanup efforts including issuing orders to owners 
