<TEXT>
congress sent a landmark savings and loan 
bailout to president bush early today after a frantic two days of 
wrangling over the finishing touches on the biggest financial 
rescue in history 
the house passed the 159 billion legislation shortly after 
midnight friday on a 201175 vote allowing weary members of 
congress to begin a monthlong vacation that had been threatened by 
a bitter fight with the administration over the financing of the 
package 
house democrats abandoned the bill in large numbers after key 
congressional negotiators bowed to a veto threat by bush and agreed 
to hide 60 percent of the bailouts cost from the federal deficit 
but with the losses of governmentinsured deposits mounting at a 
rate of 20 million to 30 million daily house and senate leaders 
from both parties with vigorous personal lobbying by bush over 
the telephone put together enough votes to replenish an insolvent 
sampl insurance fund with 50 billion 
the savings of million of americans are at stake unless we do 
something sen christopher bond rmo said just before the 
senate approved the bill on a nonroll call late thursday night 
rep chalmers wylie rohio said the nation risked another 
bank holiday similar to the wave of bank closings of 1933 when 
depositors lined up for blocks demanding their savings turning 
what was then a recession into the great depression 
the 50 billion will be used over the next three years to close 
and merge 500 insolvent sampls and pay off depositors whose savings 
were lost to failed and often fraudulent loans over the past 
decade most of them in texas 
the legislation also overhauls the regulation of the industry 
requiring owners of the nations 3000 thrift institutions to put 
up billions of dollars more of their own money as capital to serve 
as a buffer between risky loans and federal deposit insurance funds 
congress and the administration had worked out the reforms weeks 
ago leaving the sticky issue of how to pay for the bailout without 
raising taxes or dipping into other government programs as the 
major roadblock to fixing the sampl crisis 
bush insisted that the money be raised through an elaborate 
scheme using nontreasury bonds to be issued by a new government 
agency created only for that purpose as a way of keeping the 
bailout costs out of the governments official deficit figures 
democrats demanded that the money be borrowed directly through 
the treasury a move that would have swelled the deficit by 44 
billion over three years but would have reduced the 30year 
interest costs on the borrowing by 45 billion 
after bush on thursday threatened to veto the bill if it 
ballooned the deficit the two sides agreed to split the financing 
both ways 
under an accord hammered out by treasury secretary nicholas f 
brady and white house budget director richard darman with key 
lawmakers the treasury will borrow 20 billion before october 
swelling the estimated deficit for this year from 148 billion to 
168 billion 
but the nontreasury bonds will be used to raise the other 30 
billion in 1990 and 1991 raising the deficit a maximum of only 
35 billion the annual interest payments on the borrowing each 
of those years if current interest rates prevail 
just before the vote today rep sam gibbons of florida one of 
135 house democrats voting against the bill complained his 
colleagues had lost their conscience and their backbone in response 
to bushs veto threat 
it should have been paid for by taxes but the president could 
not bring himself to say the word said gibbons so we have 
fostered this unconscionable debt on our children and 
grandchildren 
by the administrations latest estimates the bailout is 
expected to cost 159 billion including interest on the borrowing 
to pay for it over the next 10 years 
over 30 years the costs mushroom to 285 billion of which 
taxpayers will pay at least 157 billion according to the 
congressional auditors in the general accounting office 
the bill also requires sampls to channel more of their lending to 
home mortgages and away from speculative commercial real estate 
ventures and highyield highrisk junk bonds 
it gives the justice department 75 million a year to root out 
fraud at financial institutions and establishes a new agency the 
resolution trust corp to dispose of 300 billion of real estate 
and other property falling into the governments hands through 
failed sampl loans 
for the first time banks will be able to buy and own healthy 
sampls their biggest lending market competitor in many communities 
and the thrift industry will be required to pour 50 million to 
100 million of its profits each year into subsidizing mortgages at 
belowmarket interest rates for lowincome families 
</TEXT>
