<TEXT>
the five miners who prospectorcannibal 
alferd g packer fed upon in the winter of 1874 were viciously 
beaten to death and their bones picked clean of flesh with knives 
researchers say 
the pangs of starvation cannot adequately and totally account 
for the brutality manifested in these killings said james 
starrs a professor of law and forensic science at george 
washington university 
what we have seen is not merely murder but butchery a 
butchery at once wholesale remorseless unremitting and 
deliberate he said at a news conference friday 
starrs organized a scientific inquiry that last month unearthed 
the bones of the five men in the san juan mountains of southwestern 
colorado 
the expedition was launched to solve one of the grisly mysteries 
of the old west the story of packer a harness maker guide and 
prospector from utah and the men he ate 
a team of 13 scientists and anthropologists using radarmapping 
equipment recovered the remains two miles south of lake city colo 
packer and five other goldseekers became snowbound on a 
9000foothigh pass in february 1874 packer walked out of the 
mountains the following april 
in his confession he admitted having eaten the others to 
survive but said he had shot one of the men shannon wilson bell 
in selfdefense when he returned to camp and found bell had 
murdered the other four with a hatchet 
there is no visible evidence for gunshot wounds on any of 
them said walter birkby director of the human identification 
laboratory at the university of arizona and curator of physical 
anthropology at the arizona state museum 
birkby a forensic anthropologist initially had said last month 
there appeared to be a bullet hole in one pelvic bone but he said 
laboratory examination showed it to be a hole caused by the canine 
tooth of a flesheating animal 
birkby said the youngest victim believed to be 17 or 19 was 
beaten the most severely he was hit at least 11 times in the 
head with an axe 
the young mans shattered upper left arm suggested that he had 
been able for a time to fend off his attacker 
the victim would have been in better shape stronger and perhaps 
better able to withstand the rigors of starvation and temperature 
than his older covictims the oldest of whom was between 50 and 
60 birkby said 
starrs said someone had an insatiable hunger whether for 
human flesh or not i am not about to say this was not mindless 
cannibalism in any sense these bodies were denuded of their flesh 
in a concerted and calculated way 
packer escaped from custody but was captured in 1883 in 
cheyenne wyo and was convicted of murdering one prospector and 
sentenced to hang the sentence was overturned on a technicality 
and on retrial he was convicted of manslaughter and given a 40year 
prison sentence 
packer died in april 1907 six years after he was paroled 
starrs said the bones will be reinterred aug 14 at lake city 
</TEXT>
