an electric motor in a british nuclear 
submarine caught fire today while the vessel was berthed in 
scotland but crewmen quickly extinguished the flames the defense 
ministry said 
no one was injured and no radioactivity leaked out ministry 
officials said 
the fire broke out shortly after midnight in an electric motor 
on the submarine hms valiant a ministry spokesman in london said 
the vessel had returned to its base in faslane on the river clyde 
in southwest scotland after a 88 million refitting 
hms valiant launched in 1963 is the royal navys oldest 
nuclearpowered submarine when on duty at sea it is armed with 
surfacetosurface conventional missiles and nonnuclear tigerfish 
torpedoes it carries a crew of 116 
the spokesman who spoke on condition of anonymity in keeping 
with british practice said the motor that caught fire is part of 
the hydraulic system he said the fire posed no danger to the crew 
or the nuclear reactor 
it was nothing to do with the nuclear side of things it was a 
mechanical problem it was nowhere near the reactor he said 
the hydraulic system drives some equipment on the submarine 
including the periscope and hatches 
the spokesman said he had no details of damage or exactly how 
the fire started however he said crewmen put it out within 15 
minutes 
