decision late to play hardball 
after rejecting a motion to recommend lucas on a 77 tie the 
committee also defeated on the same vote an attempt to report the 
nomination to the floor for further action 
this is a journey you have some things you win some things 
you lose runkel said the things you lose you learn by them 
the lucas vote last tuesday came barely a month after fiske 
withdrew from consideration for the justice departments no 2 spot 
senate republicans including strom thurmond of south carolina 
and gordon humphrey objected to fiske saying that as chairman of 
the abas judicial screening panel he had scuttled some of reagans 
nominees to the federal bench 
thornburgh tried to allay the conservatives suspicions about 
fiske last spring telling congress fiske had help negotiate an 
agreement whereby the aba consented not to evaluate a judicial 
candidates political or ideological views 
but thornburghs announcement blew up in his face hours later 
when the aba said there was no such agreement 
an angry thornburgh then threatened to cut the aba out of all 
judicial screening unless his terms were accepted 
the aba and thornburgh came to terms after a onemonth delay 
but that gave fiskes opponents more time to raise doubts about the 
appointment and fisk bowed out in early july 
something you learn is timing a lesson that can be applied 
to the lucas case as well as the fiske episode runkel said 
i dont think anybody doubts lucas would have been confirmed 
if the senate had voted on him prior to all the recent supreme 
court decisions runkel said 
lucas defended the series of high court rulings on civil rights 
that are unpopular with liberal democrats echoing the bush 
administration policy that no legislation is needed to overturn 
them 
lucass answers disturbed several democrats on the judiciary 
committee prompting thornburgh later to accuse the panel of 
applying too narrow a test on civil rights issues 
i find it somewhat bizarre to expect an appointee of the 
president to begin his career in opposition to the president in an 
important area of the law thornburgh told reporters last week 
runkel maintained that both lucas and fiske were victims of the 
politicization of the confirmation process 
democrats argued that the issue with lucas was not politics but 
qualifications 
despite that judgment runkel insists lucas is a solid guy 
who will have a position in the administration if he wants it 
the same day thornburgh lost the bitter fight with civil rights 
groups over lucas the attorney general helped negotiate compromise 
legislation to end discrimination against the nations 43 million 
americans with disabilities 
civil rights lobbyist ralph neas who fought the attorney 
general on lucas said thornburgh played a very pivotal role 
behind the scenes forging the compromise 
one of the more fascinating aspect of politics is that todays 
adversary can be tomorrows ally neas said in this case it 
was that todays adversary can be todays ally 
</TEXT>
