foreign minister eduard shevardnadze possibly as early as 
september said an aide to sen frank murkowski ralaska 
the agreement also establishes a commission of three soviets and 
three alaskans to help deal with minor incidents emergency 
evacuations and search and rescue operations said murkowski aide 
jessica gavora 
murkowski said the agreement is the most significant development 
yet in a 2yearold thaw between alaska and the soviet far east 
territories across the bering strait 
in alaska natives who live on st lawrence island the seward 
peninsula or in the kotzebue area and have cultural or family ties 
with the soviet far east are expected to qualify for visafree 
travel gavora said trips could last up to 90 days 
the federal government would determine who could go and would 
compile lists to be placed at border checkpoints 
travel would be confined to border regions 
alaska natives used to travel across the bering strait by 
motorboat to exchange walrus skins and sable fur they returned 
with flour sugar tobacco and underwear from soviet trading posts 
the agreement permitting the trips was terminated in 1948 as the 
cold war chilled relations between the united states and the soviet 
union 
with the easing of border tensions in the past two years soviet 
and alaska yupiks have renewed contacts last month bering air of 
nome began a charter service to transport groups back and forth 
