<DOCNO> AP890805-0148 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the summer pastime of economists and others who 
try to anticipate the future is whether the economy is headed for a 
soft landing a recession or neither 
opinions are as varied as the grains of sand on the beach or the 
shape of the clouds or the bubbles in a drink and for the 
practical purposes of most ordinary people it matters not a whit 
who is right 
recessions come and go no freemarket economy has ever been 
without them for long they are an economic pulse preceding and 
following expansions they are in the nature of freemarket 
economies like colds are to humans 
they might come from unexpected events such as catastrophes or 
shortages or from economic mismanagement such as misinformed 
moneysupply policies or simply because when times are good people 
push things to the extreme 
whether a recession technically occurs isnt of vast importance 
to most people more significant by far is the extent of the 
downturn in terms of jobs and job security wages profits and 
prices 
technically a recession occurs when gross national product 
declines for two successive quarters but it is possible for this 
to occur without being noticed by the ordinary working person or 
in fact by entire geographic areas 
consider it is a slowdown not a recession if economic 
expansion slows but grows by a fraction of 1 percent for two 
successive quarters but it is a recession if the economy shrinks 
by a fraction for two quarters in a row 
other criteria are considered too but past recessions usually 
have been identified by the twoquarter theory 
especially important to the ordinary person is the length of a 
recession or a slowdown some are vshaped the decline is quickly 
followed by an upturn some are ushaped and some are long and 
level as a summer horizon 
is a quick corrective recession any worse than a prolonged 
downturn that doesnt qualify as a recession stagnant economies 
that stumble along the plus side of the recessionexpansion line 
might be more destructive 
theres a geographical aspect to recessions too technically 
the nations economy can be described as in recession with some 
regions enjoying good times or the numbers can show it to be 
healthy when many areas are desperately ill 
the latter in fact occurred earlier this decade when states 
dependent on oil mining and agriculture simultaneously suffered 
economic woes for different reasons 
at one time in that period an economic research organization 
sindlinger amp co measured 33 states in recession offsetting their 
depressing effect on the national statistics were coastal areas 
with expanding economies 
there is also some evidence that recessions today need not be 
quite what they used to be due in part perhaps to more informed 
economic management and maybe to the emergence of a global economy 
if the domestic consumer economy is weak for example it might be 
offset by exports to a strong foreign economy 
some economists like to refer to rolling readjustments 
rather than recessions the term is euphemistic to some extent but 
the rationale may be sound moreover it seems to be supported by 
some recent experiences 
whatever these economists believe it is less likely today than 
yesterday for most industries to go down together and more likely 
that a recession will roll through the economy affecting different 
industries at different times 
recessions can be allinclusive or selective they can be 
extended or brief they can be deep or marginal they can be 
accompanied by price increases or decreases they can be 
significant or relatively unimportant 
not all of the species is savage while you might not like to 
make a pet of any recession some of them are quite tame 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

