<TEXT>
the junk bond market is preparing for the 
fallout from a requirement that savings and loans sell their 
holdings in these highyield high risk investments as part of the 
congressional thrift bailout bill 
some industry watchers say the elimination of savings and loans 
as a market for junk bonds could depress junk bond prices and make 
it more expensive for companies to float new highyield issues 
it is a significant pool of capital that has now been cut off 
from the highyield market of course thats going to restrict any 
market said greg scott executive vice president of the alliance 
for capital access a trade group for junk bond issuers 
others say the ban on thrift junk bond holding may not have a 
major impact 
while thrifts are important junk bond investors they dont 
comprise an enormous percentage of buying power said john j 
kriz an assistant vice president at moodys investors service 
kriz said other factors affecting the junk bond market at the 
time the thrifts sell their holdings may mitigate the effect of the 
sales among these factors are interest rates and how many new junk 
bond issues are floated 
other industry watchers say its premature to say what effect 
the bailout bills provision would have 
the provision was approved by a housesenate panel late last 
month it would give thrifts five years to sell their junk bond 
holdings so there probably wouldnt be a wholesale dumping of the 
bonds at once 
the us league of savings institutions the thrift industrys 
largest trade group said it did not lobby against the junk bond 
requirement because only about 175 of the nations 2900 savings 
and loans invest in the bonds 
of the 175 10 held about 70 percent of the 41 billion in junk 
bonds owned by the industry in the first quarter said james grohl 
a senior vice president for the trade group 
the alliance for capital access put the total junk bond 
investment by thrifts at about 14 billion whichever figure is 
correct the investment is still a small fraction of the 
approximately 200 billion junk bond market 
the alliances scott says the loss of thrifts as junk bond 
buyers would be especially troubling because it has been a 
fastgrowing market for the bonds thrift investments in junk bonds 
have doubled since 1985 he said 
but he added there are other juicy markets for junk bonds that 
have barely been penetrated such as the life insurance and mutual 
fund industries of the approximately 1 trillion in assets of life 
insurers less than 1 percent is invested in highyield securities 
scott said the ban on thrift junk bond holdings may have a 
psychological impact on the market forcing junk bond issuers to 
increase the yields of the bonds which already are substantially 
higher than treasury bonds but scott said he expected the impact 
would be temporary 
the savings and loan legislation provides a loophole for thrifts 
that want to keep their junk bonds under the bill they may form a 
separately capitalized affiliate and sell their junk bonds to it 
but scott said few thrifts would have the financial wherewithal to 
set up such a subsidiary 
junk bonds are so named because they are rated as noninvestment 
grade or speculative by the credit rating firms because of the 
higher risk of default they pay more interest to holders than 
investmentgrade bonds 
junk bonds are issued by companies that already are deep in debt 
or otherwise cannot obtain an investmentgrade rating they also 
are used to raise cash for corporate takeovers 
the alliance for capital access stands by the soundness of junk 
bonds as investments scott said he believes the divestment 
provision of the bailout bill was motivated in part because the 
bonds are used for hostile takeovers and because thrifts were using 
federally insured deposits to invest in them 
the debate was driven by emotion not facts scott said 
the pioneer and biggest booster of the junk bond market drexel 
burnham lambert inc also opposes the divestiture requirement 
no thrift has ever failed because of their investment in high 
yield bonds said spokesman steven s anreder we feel this 
action will only serve to restrict access to capital by small and 
mediumsize businesses 
